<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="theo_NormAlgebraicProperties"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Algebraic Properties of the Norm Operation</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation of <math>
               <latex>|t\cdot \Vect{x}| = |t|\cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
            </math>
         </info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>This property is intuitively quite plausible: The vector <math>
                  <latex>t\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> results from <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> by stretching or shrinking its length by a factor of <math>
                  <latex>|t|</latex>
               </math>, followed by reversing it, in case <math>
                  <latex>t</latex>
               </math> is negative. In either case, the length of the resulting vector is <math>
                  <latex>|t|\cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
               </math>, and this is exactly what the formula claims.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <associate type="Example">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Example of a Unit Vector</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>For example, the unit vector in the direction of <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}=(4,2,4)</latex>
               </math> is</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>\Vect{u} = \tfrac{1}{\abs{\Vect{x}} }\cdot \Vect{x} = \tfrac{1}{6}\cdot (4,2,4)</latex>
         </math.display>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Comment on nondegeneracy property of norm</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>In other words: there is exactly one vector in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math> whose norm is <math>
                  <latex>0</latex>
               </math>, namely the zero-vector.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>For vectors <math>
               <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
            </math>, and <math>
               <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
            </math>, and numbers <math>
               <latex>t</latex>
            </math> in <math>
               <latex>\RNr</latex>
            </math> the following hold:</para.body>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>norm</term>
            <term>of a vector: properties</term>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Click for the proposition formulating basic properties of the norm operation</para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <part.theorem partid="Prop_NormCommutesScalars">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>|t\cdot \Vect{x}| = |t|\cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="Prop_ConstructUnitVector">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>, the vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{u} := \tfrac{\Vect{x}}{|\Vect{x}|}</latex>
                  </math> has <subordinate>
                     <hot>length 1 and the same direction as <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Note how <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                              </math> is built: Start with the vector <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math>. It has length <math>
                                 <latex>|\Vect{x}|</latex>
                              </math>. Then divide <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math> by its length. So you get a vector of length <math>
                                 <latex>1</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>; we call <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                  </math> the unit vector in the direction of  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>unit</term>
                  <term>vector</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>A vector of length <math>
                              <latex>1</latex>
                           </math>; click to see how to compute the unit vector in the direction of a given nonzero vector.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="Prop_NormNonDegenerate">
         <caption>Non degeneracy of norm</caption>
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>|\Vect{x}| = 0</latex>
                  </math>   if and only if   <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>.
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>non-degenerate</term>
                  <term>norm</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The non-degeneracy property of the norm operation asserts that, for a vector <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, <math>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| = 0</latex>
                           </math> if and only if <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> is the zero vector. – Click to see why it is true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>norm</term>
                  <term>non-degeneracy</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The non-degeneracy property of the norm operation asserts that, for a vector <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, <math>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| = 0</latex>
                           </math> if and only if <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> is the zero vector. – Click to see why it is true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>Prop_NormCommutesScalars</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>
			We verify this property by direct computation:
		</caption>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>|t\cdot \Vect{x}|</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>|t\cdot (x_1,\dots ,x_n)|</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>|(tx_1,\dots ,tx_n)|</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{(tx_1)^2+\cdots + (tx_n)^2}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{t^2x_{1}^{2}+ \cdots + t^2x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{t^2(x_{1}^{2}+\cdots + x_{n}^{2})}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>|t|\cdot \sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots +x_{n}^{2}}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>|t|\cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>as was to be shown.</para.body>
         </para>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>Prop_ConstructUnitVector</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>
			We verify this property by direct computation:
		</caption>
         <para align="center">
            <para.body>
               <math>
                  <latex>\left| \frac{\Vect{x}}{|\Vect{x}|} \right|</latex>
               </math>
               <subordinate>
                  <hot>
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Here we use the previous property of the norm operation: <math>
                              <latex>|t\cdot \Vect{x}| = |t|\cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
               <math>
                  <latex>|1/|\Vect{x}| | \cdot |\Vect{x}|</latex>
               </math>
               <subordinate>
                  <hot>
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Here we use that <math>
                              <latex>|\Vect{x}| &gt; 0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
               <math>
                  <latex>= 1</latex>
               </math>
            </para.body>
         </para>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>Prop_NormNonDegenerate</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>
			Non degeneracy of norm:
		</caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>If <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
               </math>, consider first the case where <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}= \Vect{0}</latex>
               </math>. In this case <math>
                  <latex>|\Vect{x}| = \sqrt{0^2+\cdots +0^2} = 0</latex>
               </math>. So, as expected: the zero vector has norm <math>
                  <latex>0</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>For the converse, suppose <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> satisfies <math>
                  <latex>|\Vect{x}| = 0</latex>
               </math>. We verify by direct computation that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
               </math>. Indeed, we have</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>0 = |\Vect{x}|^2 = x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2}</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>Each of the squares on the right is greater than or equal to <math>
                  <latex>0</latex>
               </math>. So, if the sum of these squares vanishes, so must each square by itself. Therefore <math>
                  <latex>x_1=\cdots =x_n=0</latex>
               </math>; i.e. <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}=\Vect{0}</latex>
               </math> as claimed.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
